00:44:57.279 --> 00:45:02.140
I want you to think about the people who did
nothing because all but one of those officers

00:45:02.140 --> 00:45:04.859
did nothing.

00:45:04.859 --> 00:45:06.500
What do we think about them?

00:45:06.500 --> 00:45:12.680
Now, I ask this question because as I think
about the problem this nation faces increasingly,

00:45:12.680 --> 00:45:16.069
I believe we are they.

00:45:16.069 --> 00:45:21.319
This nation faces critical problems requiring
serious attention, but we don't have institutions

00:45:21.319 --> 00:45:23.000
capable of giving them this attention.

00:45:23.000 --> 00:45:27.950
They are distracted, unable to focus.

00:45:27.950 --> 00:45:29.819
And who is to blame for that?

00:45:29.819 --> 00:45:34.529
Who is responsible?

00:45:34.529 --> 00:45:40.200
I think it's too easy to point to the Blagojeviches
and hold them responsible, to point to the

00:45:40.200 --> 00:45:42.569
evil people and hold them responsible.

00:45:42.569 --> 00:45:43.730
It's not the evil people.

00:45:43.730 --> 00:45:45.999
It’s the good people.

00:45:45.999 --> 00:45:47.740
It's the decent people.

00:45:47.740 --> 00:45:49.880
It's the people who could've picked up a phone.

00:45:49.880 --> 00:45:52.079
It's us.

00:45:52.079 --> 00:45:55.140
It's we, the most privileged.

00:45:55.140 --> 00:45:59.359
Because the most outrageous part here is that
these corruptions, of course, were primed

00:45:59.359 --> 00:46:06.160
by the most privileged, but they were permitted
by the passivity of the most privileged as

00:46:06.160 --> 00:46:09.420
well--permitted by us.

00:46:09.420 --> 00:46:15.569
When Ben Franklin was carried from the Constitutional
Convention in the summer of 1787, a woman

00:46:15.569 --> 00:46:19.029
stopped him on the street and said, "Mr. Franklin,
what have you wrought?"

00:46:19.029 --> 00:46:25.289
Franklin replied, "A republic, ma'am, if you
can keep it."

00:46:25.289 --> 00:46:28.369
A republic.

00:46:28.369 --> 00:46:30.410
A representative democracy.

00:46:30.410 --> 00:46:36.950
A democracy dependent upon the people alone.

00:46:36.950 --> 00:46:46.359
We have lost that republic and all of us have
to work to get it back.

00:46:46.359 --> 00:46:53.259
Thank you very much.

00:46:53.259 --> 00:46:54.989
[applause]

00:46:54.989 --> 00:47:03.609
I'm happy to take questions.

00:47:03.609 --> 00:47:09.170
I'm a law professor, so I could call on people
if you don't ask questions.

00:47:09.170 --> 00:47:10.170
[laughter]

00:47:10.170 --> 00:47:11.239
Yes, sir.

00:47:11.239 --> 00:47:16.750
&gt;&gt;MALE #1: Do you have any opinions on electoral
reform?

00:47:16.750 --> 00:47:20.759
I can't vote for the party I want 'cause if
I vote for anybody other than Republicans

00:47:20.759 --> 00:47:22.999
or Democrats, my vote is wasted.

00:47:22.999 --> 00:47:23.999
&gt;&gt;Lawrence Lessig: Yeah.

00:47:23.999 --> 00:47:28.509
I think that there's a whole list of other
reforms that we also need to think about with

00:47:28.509 --> 00:47:29.509
democracy.

00:47:29.509 --> 00:47:35.029
The way we gerrymander districts, the way
we have winner-take-all seats.

00:47:35.029 --> 00:47:37.940
All of these things I think are critically
important, too.

00:47:37.940 --> 00:47:41.700
I'm trying to think about the sequence of
problems.

00:47:41.700 --> 00:47:45.380
And I think the sequence of problems is, this
is the problem we need to solve first to create

00:47:45.380 --> 00:47:48.309
an atmosphere, an opportunity, to begin to
address the other problems.

00:47:48.309 --> 00:47:53.480
So, I'm happy to sign up with you on that
once we fix the problem I'm talking about

00:47:53.480 --> 00:47:54.480
here first.

00:47:54.480 --> 00:47:55.480
Yeah.

00:47:55.480 --> 00:47:56.480
&gt;&gt;MALE #2: Hi.

00:47:56.480 --> 00:47:57.480
Two quick questions.

00:47:57.480 --> 00:47:59.750
The first is, what's the name of the Senator
that came up with the little bastards that

00:47:59.750 --> 00:48:01.549
are greedy in the greedy bastards quote?

00:48:01.549 --> 00:48:05.469
&gt;&gt;Lawrence Lessig: He would not go on the
record with him name, [audience chuckles]

00:48:05.469 --> 00:48:09.229
so the Huffington Post piece says it's an
anonymous Senator who said this.

00:48:09.229 --> 00:48:10.650
&gt;&gt;MALE #2: OK.

00:48:10.650 --> 00:48:14.420
Secondly, about the Constitution Convention,
using say, legislatures.

00:48:14.420 --> 00:48:17.690
How are the state representatives gonna be
different from the national representatives?

00:48:17.690 --> 00:48:22.119
'Cause aren't they just as greedy and looking
to climb the ladder of political opportunity?

00:48:22.119 --> 00:48:27.160
&gt;&gt;Lawrence Lessig: Yeah, so state legislatures
just passed resolutions calling on the Convention.

00:48:27.160 --> 00:48:29.530
And the question is, how do you populate the
Convention?

00:48:29.530 --> 00:48:34.140
And here's the really insane, totally completely
insane idea, that I have for the Convention.

00:48:34.140 --> 00:48:38.660
I think the Convention should be populated
by a random selection, random proportional

00:48:38.660 --> 00:48:40.630
selection, of citizens.

00:48:40.630 --> 00:48:44.460
Now, people think that's crazy.

00:48:44.460 --> 00:48:45.460
And I agree.

00:48:45.460 --> 00:48:47.589
You're not gonna argue anybody into insanity.

00:48:47.589 --> 00:48:54.249
I think what you've gotta do is to show them,
like let's run 30 or 40 or 50 of these mock

00:48:54.249 --> 00:48:58.820
Constitutional Conventions where we have deliberative
polls where we randomly select a representative

00:48:58.820 --> 00:49:03.440
mix of people from a jurisdiction and we give
them the information they need.

00:49:03.440 --> 00:49:06.900
And we have them work through the issue and
see what they come up with.

00:49:06.900 --> 00:49:08.380
California has a good example of this.

00:49:08.380 --> 00:49:12.490
The California Forward Project ran a deliberative
project, deliberative poll, around the question

00:49:12.490 --> 00:49:14.039
of what California should do.

00:49:14.039 --> 00:49:18.489
And the product of that is extraordinarily
impressive--much better than anything the

00:49:18.489 --> 00:49:20.479
professionals did.

00:49:20.479 --> 00:49:25.450
And I think that signals the core insight,
which is politics is one of these rare sports

00:49:25.450 --> 00:49:28.569
where the amateurs are actually better than
the professional.

00:49:28.569 --> 00:49:33.890
Because the professional is good at figuring
out how to benefit the special interests that

00:49:33.890 --> 00:49:35.880
the professional depends upon.

00:49:35.880 --> 00:49:41.380
And the amateur, like a jury, can be summoned
into a state where they're not thinking so

00:49:41.380 --> 00:49:42.869
much about the special interest.

00:49:42.869 --> 00:49:47.309
So, I think the only way a Convention makes
sense is if we can avoid it being captured

00:49:47.309 --> 00:49:49.569
in exactly the same way government has been
captured.

00:49:49.569 --> 00:49:54.999
And I think the only way to that is to have
this randomly selected body be the Convention.

00:49:54.999 --> 00:50:00.759
&gt;&gt;MALE #3: First of all, thank you so much
for being here and for devoting so much time

00:50:00.759 --> 00:50:01.859
to this very important issue.

00:50:01.859 --> 00:50:02.859
&gt;&gt;Lawrence Lessig: Thank you.

00:50:02.859 --> 00:50:11.039
&gt;&gt;MALE #3: My question is, given the election
of Obama in 2008, and then the following three

00:50:11.039 --> 00:50:17.989
years, how much of the overwhelming Democratic
majorities and the election Obama have helped

00:50:17.989 --> 00:50:21.489
the momentum of this campaign finance reform
campaign?

00:50:21.489 --> 00:50:25.900
In that, I think there's a lot of people who
sort of generally understand the Republicans

00:50:25.900 --> 00:50:32.920
were bought, but I think when the nation was
rallied around this feeling in 2008, and then

00:50:32.920 --> 00:50:36.109
the disappointment that's come out of it,
I just--.

00:50:36.109 --> 00:50:37.710
&gt;&gt;Lawrence Lessig: Yeah.

00:50:37.710 --> 00:50:42.650
You and I share that view precisely.

00:50:42.650 --> 00:50:43.650
The book is--.

00:50:43.650 --> 00:50:44.799
Obama was a friend.

00:50:44.799 --> 00:50:46.680
He was a colleague of mine in Chicago.

00:50:46.680 --> 00:50:48.190
I campaigned for him.

00:50:48.190 --> 00:50:49.190
I worked hard for him.

00:50:49.190 --> 00:50:54.420
I talked to a lot of people in here when he
first was on the trail about how he'd be so

00:50:54.420 --> 00:50:56.969
great for what we cared about.

00:50:56.969 --> 00:51:02.039
But the only reason I think he was credible
as a candidate over Hilary Clinton, was that

00:51:02.039 --> 00:51:05.270
he, unlike Hilary Clinton, said, "This system
is the problem.

00:51:05.270 --> 00:51:07.959
We have to take up the fight to change the
way Washington works.

00:51:07.959 --> 00:51:11.680
And if we don't, our children are gonna be
facing the same problems we faced.

00:51:11.680 --> 00:51:14.540
And our children's children will be facing
the same problems they face."

00:51:14.540 --> 00:51:15.759
So, he made it--.

00:51:15.759 --> 00:51:21.749
He said twice at least, I have recorded in
the campaign, "This is the reason I am running.

00:51:21.749 --> 00:51:22.809
To change the system."

00:51:22.809 --> 00:51:26.809
And then he got elected and he opened up the
Clinton playbook.

00:51:26.809 --> 00:51:30.549
And he ran his Administration according to
the way Hilary Clinton would've run her Administration.

00:51:30.549 --> 00:51:32.069
And I think maybe Clinton would have done
a better job.

00:51:32.069 --> 00:51:33.069
I don't know.

00:51:33.069 --> 00:51:38.209
But if Clinton had done exactly what Barack
Obama did, I think we should say, "Great.

00:51:38.209 --> 00:51:41.039
You did what would come from that kind of
Administration.

00:51:41.039 --> 00:51:44.940
But you promised, Barack Obama, a different
Administration."

00:51:44.940 --> 00:51:49.339
I feel it's a betrayal from what we thought
we were getting.

00:51:49.339 --> 00:51:55.289
It makes it really hard for any of us to believe
that reform is gonna come from the top or

00:51:55.289 --> 00:51:56.720
from any insider.

00:51:56.720 --> 00:52:03.369
So, I think that this is why it becomes critical
to think about these outside traditional politics

00:52:03.369 --> 00:52:08.539
solutions, which is unfortunately, I think,
the only path we've got right now.

00:52:08.539 --> 00:52:10.609
He doesn't stand credible on this issue.

00:52:10.609 --> 00:52:13.230
The one person who is credible on this issue
is--.

00:52:13.230 --> 00:52:18.559
I will vote for Obama over any Republican
except one.

00:52:18.559 --> 00:52:20.759
The Republican you've not heard of.

00:52:20.759 --> 00:52:22.029
His name is Buddy Roemer.

00:52:22.029 --> 00:52:24.150
Now, it's funny you haven't heard of him.

00:52:24.150 --> 00:52:25.150
I mean, he was a governor.

00:52:25.150 --> 00:52:26.239
He was a four-term Congressman.

00:52:26.239 --> 00:52:30.690
He ran a bank for 20 years without taking
government bailouts and successfully created

00:52:30.690 --> 00:52:32.119
this community bank.

00:52:32.119 --> 00:52:36.670
But he has made a pledge in his campaign for
the Republican nomination for President where

00:52:36.670 --> 00:52:39.539
he will take no more than a hundred dollars
from anybody.

00:52:39.539 --> 00:52:44.400
He will commit to no PAC money, full disclosure,
because he wants to as his slogan, "It's free

00:52:44.400 --> 00:52:45.400
to lead."

00:52:45.400 --> 00:52:47.759
But because he takes no more than a hundred
dollars, everybody says, "Well, you can't

00:52:47.759 --> 00:52:50.470
possibly win so, we're not even gonna pay
attention to you."

00:52:50.470 --> 00:52:55.140
So, he hasn't even had a chance to make this
case in the debate.

00:52:55.140 --> 00:52:59.690
But if Buddy Roemer were the candidate in
the Republican side, that would be a game-changer.

00:52:59.690 --> 00:53:03.910
If it were a Republican making this argument,
then it would be much easier to imagine this

00:53:03.910 --> 00:53:05.529
argument actually having play.

00:53:05.529 --> 00:53:08.099
&gt;&gt;MALE #3: Thank you.

00:53:08.099 --> 00:53:12.329
&gt;&gt;MALE #4: Thank you for coming to talk to
us today.

00:53:12.329 --> 00:53:13.920
I have a question about--.

00:53:13.920 --> 00:53:18.369
I think we all can understand that there's
obviously a role that Congress has in perpetuating

00:53:18.369 --> 00:53:19.369
this system.

00:53:19.369 --> 00:53:23.180
And there's a role that we all have in our
lack of action in perpetuating this system.

00:53:23.180 --> 00:53:25.516
But I think one thing, you didn't get a chance
to talk about and I don't know if you talk

00:53:25.516 --> 00:53:30.799
about it in your book--I look forward to reading
it--is the role of the Supreme Court and notably

00:53:30.799 --> 00:53:33.839
one of your own bosses.

00:53:33.839 --> 00:53:38.999
And how you talk about the people want to
be more involved, but at this point, the Supreme

00:53:38.999 --> 00:53:46.559
Court has defined "person" to be an incredibly
broad system and how we can move away from

00:53:46.559 --> 00:53:51.039
treating corporations as people without their
movement and how we can actually affect meaningful

00:53:51.039 --> 00:53:53.440
change without movement on the Supreme Court.

00:53:53.440 --> 00:53:57.380
And a Supreme Court that seems very unlikely
to move on that particular issue.

00:53:57.380 --> 00:53:58.380
&gt;&gt;Lawrence Lessig: Yeah.

00:53:58.380 --> 00:54:03.229
So, the particular version of public funding
that I advance is completely immune from Supreme

00:54:03.229 --> 00:54:07.910
Court invalidation.

00:54:07.910 --> 00:54:12.049
Nothing in the Supreme Court, even this Supreme
Court's doctrine, would draw this type of

00:54:12.049 --> 00:54:13.140
public funding into the out.

00:54:13.140 --> 00:54:20.150
But it leaves the problem of independent expenditures,
both of individuals, George Soros or the Koch

00:54:20.150 --> 00:54:24.799
Brothers, as well as corporations, which now
have unlimited amounts to spend.

00:54:24.799 --> 00:54:29.279
And it took a comedian to teach the Supreme
Court that, in fact, they didn't have to be

00:54:29.279 --> 00:54:32.990
disclosed if they all could be secret because
you could channel them through a C4 that would

00:54:32.990 --> 00:54:36.719
itself be identified, but the contributors
to the C4 not.

00:54:36.719 --> 00:54:37.719
OK.

00:54:37.719 --> 00:54:39.849
So, we have to address the problem of independent
expenditures.

00:54:39.849 --> 00:54:43.599
Now, my view is the law should not ban anybody
from saying anything.

00:54:43.599 --> 00:54:46.780
I think corporations should have a right to
participate.

00:54:46.780 --> 00:54:52.650
But they shouldn't be able to dominate the
political process so that we have not just

00:54:52.650 --> 00:54:58.150
shape-shifting to appeal to the funders, but
we have shape-shifting to appeal to the independent

00:54:58.150 --> 00:55:03.420
expenditure guys and therefore, the same kind
of dependency that corrupts the system.

00:55:03.420 --> 00:55:09.589
So, the only way to get there without imagining
a Supreme Court reversing itself is to give

00:55:09.589 --> 00:55:13.719
Congress the power to limit, but not to ban,
independent expenditures.

00:55:13.719 --> 00:55:17.539
And if you're gonna change the Constitution
from that standpoint, I say let's have an

00:55:17.539 --> 00:55:19.309
amendment that has three components.

00:55:19.309 --> 00:55:23.289
Number one, public elections must be publicly
funded.

00:55:23.289 --> 00:55:26.150
Number two, contributions to candidates should
be capped.

00:55:26.150 --> 00:55:29.809
I'd say at a hundred dollars--equivalent of
a hundred dollars.

00:55:29.809 --> 00:55:35.660
Number three, Congress has to have the power
to limit, but not to ban, independent expenditures

00:55:35.660 --> 00:55:37.279
of both corporations and people.

00:55:37.279 --> 00:55:41.269
It just has to have the capacity to create
a time for election that's not just about

00:55:41.269 --> 00:55:42.900
the money.

00:55:42.900 --> 00:55:47.099
But getting to the place that we can have
the chance to have that amendment passed,

00:55:47.099 --> 00:55:52.010
is the hard thing because again, I looked
it up, there's zero chance Congress is gonna

00:55:52.010 --> 00:55:53.099
propose such an amendment.

00:55:53.099 --> 00:55:57.150
And so, if Congress is not gonna propose the
amendment, what's the path to get it at least

00:55:57.150 --> 00:55:58.660
on the table for states to adopt?

00:55:58.660 --> 00:56:00.420
&gt;&gt;MALE #4: Thank you very much.

00:56:00.420 --> 00:56:01.420
&gt;&gt;Lawrence Lessig: Yup.

00:56:01.420 --> 00:56:02.420
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #1: Hi.

00:56:02.420 --> 00:56:08.619
I'm wondering about your perspective on venture
philanthropy and the role of money outside

00:56:08.619 --> 00:56:10.029
the congressional system.

00:56:10.029 --> 00:56:11.359
Is it a pure good?

00:56:11.359 --> 00:56:15.950
I'm thinking, for example, of education reform,
the Charter School movement, that sort of

00:56:15.950 --> 00:56:16.950
thing.

00:56:16.950 --> 00:56:20.699
Or, is there some danger there that money
is talking more than it ought to, even in

00:56:20.699 --> 00:56:21.699
those worlds?

00:56:21.699 --> 00:56:22.699
&gt;&gt;Lawrence Lessig: Yeah.

00:56:22.699 --> 00:56:23.699
It's a great question.

00:56:23.699 --> 00:56:27.369
I don't think you can say without reservations
that it's good.

00:56:27.369 --> 00:56:32.390
Although, you can say it's really great that
it's out there, right?

00:56:32.390 --> 00:56:40.289
There are foundations that are not disciplined
enough to insulate and protect the recipients

00:56:40.289 --> 00:56:43.699
from developing the wrong kind of dependency
on the foundation.

00:56:43.699 --> 00:56:47.279
So, it distorts them in a way that I think
is not productive.

00:56:47.279 --> 00:56:48.719
And so, harmful.

00:56:48.719 --> 00:56:54.839
But I think there are others that adopt a
very appropriate relationship to the targets

00:56:54.839 --> 00:56:58.849
of their giving that allows them to maintain
their independence, but does support their

00:56:58.849 --> 00:56:59.849
work.

00:56:59.849 --> 00:57:03.729
So, I think in a case-by-case way, we gotta
make a decision about what's the appropriate

00:57:03.729 --> 00:57:05.739
kind of relationship to be drawing in that
case.

00:57:05.739 --> 00:57:07.369
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #1: Thank you.

00:57:07.369 --> 00:57:12.189
&gt;&gt;MALE #5: So, we're out of time to take more
questions, but thanks again for coming.

00:57:12.189 --> 00:57:13.189
&gt;&gt;Lawrence Lessig: Thank you.

00:57:13.189 --> 00:57:14.189
Thanks a lot.

00:57:14.189 --> 00:57:14.190
[applause]

